    and Cultural Research in Minnesota. He is author of <i>Allen Tate and the 
    Catholic Revival</i> (Paulist Press, 1996) and <i>What Are They Saying About 
    Fundamentalisms?</i> (Paulist Press, 2008). 
    <P> 
    <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><B>James L. Huston</b> 
    has written <i>The Panic of 1857 and the Coming of the Civil War</i> (1987), 
    <i>Securing the Fruits of Labor: The American Concept of Wealth Distribution, 
    1765-1900</i> (1998), <i>Calculating the Value of the Union: Slavery, Property 
    Rights and the Economic Origins of the Civil War</i> (2003), and <i>Stephen 
    A. Douglas and the Dilemmas of Democratic Equality</i> (2007). He is currently 
    investigating the economic history of the United States in the nineteenth 
    century and its relationship to the free labor ideology. 
    <p> 
    <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><B>M. Thomas Inge</B><a name="inge"></a> 
